WEBVTT

00:23.560 --> 00:25.700
CHAPTER XXXI.

00:26.500 --> 00:33.520
My home, then, when I at last find a home, is a cottage, a little room with white-washed

00:33.520 --> 00:39.700
walls and a sanded floor, containing four painted chairs and a table, a clock, a cupboard,

00:40.100 --> 00:45.880
with two or three plates and dishes, and a set of teethings in delft. Above, a chamber

00:45.880 --> 00:51.840
of the same dimensions as the kitchen, with a deal bedstead, and chest of drawers, small,

00:51.840 --> 00:57.140
yet too large to be filled with my scanty wardrobe, though the kindness of my gentle

00:57.140 --> 01:02.520
and generous friends has increased that by a modest stock of such things as are necessary.

01:03.440 --> 01:08.920
It is evening. I have dismissed, with the fee of an orange, the little orphan who serves

01:08.920 --> 01:16.180
as a handmaid. I am sitting alone on the hearth. This morning the village school opened. I

01:16.180 --> 01:23.380
had twenty scholars, but three of the number can read, none write or cipher, several knit,

01:23.540 --> 01:29.780
and a few sew a little. They speak with the broadest accent of the district. At present

01:29.780 --> 01:35.800
they and I have a difficulty in understanding each other's language. Some of them are unmannered,

01:35.980 --> 01:42.280
rough, intractable, as well as ignorant, but others are docile, have a wish to learn, and

01:42.280 --> 01:48.040
a disposition that pleases me. I must not forget that these coarsely clad little peasants

01:48.040 --> 01:54.120
are of flesh and blood as good as the scions of gentlest genealogy, and that the germs

01:54.120 --> 02:00.640
of native excellence, refinement, intelligence, kind feeling, are as likely to exist in their

02:00.640 --> 02:06.880
hearts as in those of the best born. My duty will be to develop these germs. Surely I shall

02:06.880 --> 02:13.040
some happiness in discharging that office. Much enjoyment I do not expect in the life

02:13.040 --> 02:19.200
opening before me, yet it will, doubtless, if I regulate my mind, and exert my powers

02:19.200 --> 02:25.960
as I ought, yield me enough to live on from day to day. Was I very gleeful, settled, content,

02:26.300 --> 02:30.740
during the hours I passed in yonder bare, humble classroom this morning and afternoon?

02:31.460 --> 02:40.600
Not to deceive myself, I must reply, no. I felt desolate to a degree. I felt, yes, idiot

02:40.600 --> 02:46.800
that I am. I felt degraded. I doubted I had taken a step which sank instead of rising

02:46.800 --> 02:52.600
me in the scale of social existence. I was weakly dismayed at the ignorance, the poverty,

02:52.780 --> 02:57.760
the coarseness of all I heard and saw round me. But let me not hate and despise myself

02:57.760 --> 03:04.340
too much for these feelings. I know them to be wrong. That is a great step gained. I shall

03:04.340 --> 03:09.440
strive to overcome them. To-morrow, I trust, I shall get the better of them partially,

03:09.760 --> 03:14.880
and in a few weeks, perhaps, they will be quite subdued. In a few months, it is possible

03:14.880 --> 03:20.280
the happiness of seeing progress, and a change for the better in my scholars, may substitute

03:20.280 --> 03:22.080
gratification for disgust.

03:23.380 --> 03:30.260
Meantime, let me ask myself one question. Which is better? To have surrendered to temptation,

03:30.840 --> 03:36.740
listened to passion, made no painful effort, no struggle, but to have sunk down in the

03:36.740 --> 03:41.860
silken snare, fallen asleep on the flowers covering it, wakening in a southern clime

03:41.860 --> 03:47.760
amongst the luxuries of a pleasure villa, to have been now living in France, Mr. Rochester's

03:47.760 --> 03:53.720
mistress, delirious with his love half my time, for he would, oh yes, he would have

03:53.720 --> 04:00.740
loved me well for a while. He did love me. No one will ever love me so again. I shall

04:00.740 --> 04:06.380
never more know the sweet homage given to beauty, youth, and grace, for never to anyone

04:06.380 --> 04:13.040
else shall I seem to possess these charms. He was fond and proud of me. It is what no

04:13.040 --> 04:15.020
man besides will ever be.

04:15.580 --> 04:21.360
But where am I wandering, and what am I saying, and above all feeling? Whether is it better,

04:21.400 --> 04:27.060
I ask, to be a slave to a fool's paradise at Marseilles, fevered with delusive bliss

04:27.060 --> 04:33.020
one hour, suffocating with the bitterest tears of remorse and shame the next? Or to be a

04:33.020 --> 04:38.640
village a school mistress, free and honest, in a breezy mountain nook in the healthy heart

04:38.640 --> 04:45.360
of England? Yes, I feel now that I was right when I adhered to principle and law, and scorned

04:45.360 --> 04:51.080
and crushed the insane promptings of a frenzied moment. God directed me to a correct choice.

04:51.540 --> 04:57.360
I thank his providence for the guidance. Having brought my eventide musings to this point,

04:57.720 --> 05:03.840
I rose, went to my door, and looked at the sunset of the harvest day, and at the quiet

05:03.840 --> 05:09.280
fields before my cottage, which, with the school, was distant half a mile from the village.

05:10.040 --> 05:17.300
The birds were singing their last strains. The air was mild and dew was balm. While I

05:17.300 --> 05:23.060
looked, I thought myself happy, and was surprised to find myself air-long weeping. And why?

05:23.380 --> 05:29.640
For the doom which had roughed me from adhesion to my master, for him I was no more to see.

05:29.910 --> 05:36.480
For the desperate grief and fatal fury, consequences of my departure, which might now, perhaps,

05:36.580 --> 05:41.800
be dragging him from the path of right, too far to leave hope of ultimate restoration

05:41.800 --> 05:48.220
thither. At this thought, I turned my face aside from the lovely sky of Eve and lonely

05:48.220 --> 05:54.520
vale of Morton. I say lonely, for in that bend of it, visible to me, there was no building

05:54.520 --> 06:00.320
apparent, save the church and the parsonage, half hidden trees, and, quite at the extremity,

06:00.660 --> 06:06.800
the roof of Vale Hall, where the rich Mr. Oliver and his daughter lived. I hid my eyes,

06:07.040 --> 06:12.480
and linked my head against the stone frame of my door. But soon a slight noise near the

06:12.480 --> 06:18.600
wicket which, shut in my tiny garden from the meadow beyond, it made me look up. A dog,

06:18.980 --> 06:25.600
old Carlo, Mr. Rivers's pointer, as I saw in a moment, was pushing the gate with his

06:25.600 --> 06:33.100
nose, and St. John himself leaned upon it with folded arms. His brow knit, his gaze

06:33.100 --> 06:38.200
grave almost to displeasure fixed on me. I asked him to come in.

06:38.520 --> 06:44.180
No, I cannot stay. I have only brought you a little parcel my sister's left for you.

06:44.180 --> 06:51.000
I think it contains a color box, pencils, and paper. I approached to take it. A welcome

06:51.000 --> 06:56.820
gift it was. He examined my face, I thought, with austerity as I came near. The traces

06:56.820 --> 06:59.720
of tears were doubtless very visible upon it.

07:00.440 --> 07:04.460
Have you found your first day's work harder than you expected? he asked.

07:05.620 --> 07:11.660
Oh, no, on the contrary. I think in time I shall get on with my scholars very well. But

07:11.660 --> 07:16.920
perhaps your accommodations, your cottage, your furniture, have disappointed your expectations.

07:17.420 --> 07:20.820
They are, in truth, scanty enough, but—

07:20.820 --> 07:28.000
I interrupted. My cottage is clean and weatherproof, my furniture sufficient and commodious. All

07:28.000 --> 07:33.560
I see has made me thankful, not despondent. I am not absolutely such a fool and sensualist

07:33.560 --> 07:40.080
as to regret the absence of a carpet, a sofa, and silver plate. Besides, five weeks ago

07:40.080 --> 07:45.920
I had nothing. I was an outcast, a beggar, a vagrant. Now I have acquaintance, a home,

07:45.980 --> 07:51.860
a business. I wonder at the goodness of God, the generosity of my friends, the bounty of

07:51.860 --> 07:58.020
my lot. I do not repine. But you feel solitude and oppression? The little house there behind

07:58.020 --> 08:03.860
you is dark and empty. I have hardly had time yet to enjoy a sense of tranquillity, much

08:03.860 --> 08:06.080
less to grow impatient under one of loneliness.

08:06.720 --> 08:12.220
Very well. I hope you feel the content you express. At any rate, your good sense will

08:12.220 --> 08:17.720
tell you that it is too soon yet to yield to the vacillating fears of Lot's wife. What

08:17.720 --> 08:22.760
you had left before I saw you, of course, I do not know. But I counsel you to resist

08:22.760 --> 08:28.460
firmly every temptation which would incline you to look back. Pursue your present career

08:29.180 --> 08:30.900
steadily—for some months, at least.

08:31.460 --> 08:38.300
It is what I mean to do, I answered. St. John continued. It is hard work to control the

08:38.300 --> 08:42.640
workings of inclination and turn the bent of nature, but that it may be done I know

08:42.640 --> 08:48.900
from experience. God has given us, in a measure, the power to make our own fate, and when our

08:48.900 --> 08:54.100
energies seem to demand a sustenance they cannot get, when our will strains after a

08:54.100 --> 08:59.800
path we may not follow, we need neither starve from inanation nor stand still in despair.

08:59.800 --> 09:05.020
We have but to seek another nourishment for the mind, as strong as the forbidden food

09:05.020 --> 09:11.940
it longed to taste, and perhaps purer, and to hew out for the adventurous foot a road

09:11.940 --> 09:17.160
as direct and broad as the one fortune has blocked up against us, if rougher than it.

09:18.100 --> 09:23.020
A year ago I was myself intensely miserable, because I thought I had made a mistake in

09:23.020 --> 09:28.340
entering the ministry. Its uniform duties wearied me to death. I burnt for the more

09:28.340 --> 09:33.860
active life of the world, for the more exciting toils of a literary career, for the destiny

09:33.860 --> 09:39.520
of an artist, author, orator, something rather than that of a priest, yes, the heart of a

09:39.520 --> 09:46.820
politician, of a soldier, of a votary of glory, a lover of renown, a luster after power beat

09:46.820 --> 09:53.880
under my curate surplus. I considered. My life was so wretched it must be changed or

09:53.880 --> 10:01.880
die. After a season of darkness and struggling, light broke and relief fell. My cramped existence

10:01.880 --> 10:08.200
all at once spread out to a plain without bounds. My powers heard a call from heaven to rise,

10:08.900 --> 10:16.100
gather their full strength, spread their wings, and mount beyond ken. God has an errand for me,

10:16.200 --> 10:22.620
to bear which afar, to deliver it well, skill and strength, courage and eloquence, the best

10:22.620 --> 10:28.540
qualifications of soldier, statesman and orator were all needed. For these all center in the good

10:28.540 --> 10:34.100
missionary. A missionary I resolved to be. From that moment my state of mind changed,

10:34.240 --> 10:38.920
the fetters dissolved and dropped from every faculty, leaving nothing of bondage but its

10:38.920 --> 10:45.060
galling soreness, which time can only heal. My father, indeed, imposed the determination,

10:45.380 --> 10:51.400
but since his death I have not a legitimate obstacle to contend with. Some affairs settled,

10:51.400 --> 10:57.020
a successor for Morton provided, an entanglement or two of the feelings broken through or cut

10:57.020 --> 11:03.340
asunder, a last conflict with human weakness, in which I know I shall overcome, because I have

11:03.340 --> 11:10.880
vowed that I will overcome. And I leave Europe for the East. He said this in his peculiar subdued,

11:10.920 --> 11:16.740
yet emphatic voice, looking when he had ceased speaking not at me, but at the setting sun,

11:16.740 --> 11:22.420
at which I looked, too. Both he and I had our backs towards the path, leading up the

11:22.420 --> 11:27.860
field to the wicket. We had heard no step on that grass-grown track. The water running in

11:27.860 --> 11:33.320
the vale was the one lulling sound of the hour and scene. We might well then start when a gay

11:33.320 --> 11:39.520
voice, sweet as a silver bell, exclaimed, Good evening, Mr. Rivers. And good evening, old Carlo.

11:39.860 --> 11:44.620
Your dog is quicker to recognize his friends than you are, sir. He pricked his ears and

11:44.620 --> 11:49.260
wagged his tail when I was at the bottom of the field. And you have your back towards me now.

11:49.740 --> 11:54.940
It was true. Though Mr. Rivers had started at the first of those musical accents,

11:55.300 --> 12:00.860
as if a thunderbolt had split a cloud over his head, he stood yet, at the close of the sentence,

12:01.160 --> 12:06.320
in the same attitude in which the speaker had surprised him. His arm resting on the gate,

12:06.660 --> 12:13.300
his face directed towards the West. He turned at last with measured deliberation. A vision,

12:13.300 --> 12:18.620
as it seemed to me, had risen at his side. There appeared, within three feet of him,

12:18.860 --> 12:26.380
a form clad in pure white, a youthful graceful form, full yet fine in contour, and when,

12:26.400 --> 12:31.380
after bending to caress Carlo, it lifted up its head and threw back a long veil,

12:31.940 --> 12:38.440
there bloomed under his glance a face of perfect beauty. Perfect beauty is a strong expression,

12:38.440 --> 12:44.380
but I do not retrace or qualify it. As sweet features as ever the temperate clime of Albion

12:44.380 --> 12:51.900
moulded, as pure hues of rose and lily as ever her humid gales and vapoury skies generated and

12:51.900 --> 12:58.920
screened justified in this instance the term, no charm was wanting, no defect was perceptible.

12:59.180 --> 13:05.060
The young girl had regular and delicate lineaments, eyes shaped and coloured as we see them in lovely

13:05.060 --> 13:10.900
pictures, large and dark and full, the long and shadowy eyelash which encircles a fine eye

13:10.900 --> 13:18.160
with so soft a fascination, the penciled brow which gives such clearness, the white smooth forehead

13:18.160 --> 13:25.200
which adds such repose to the livelier beauties of tint and ray, the cheek oval fresh and smooth,

13:25.560 --> 13:32.600
the lips fresh too, ruddy, healthy, sweetly formed, the even and gleaming teeth without flaw,

13:32.600 --> 13:39.960
the small dimpled chin, the ornament of rich plenteous tresses, all advantages, in short,

13:40.260 --> 13:47.140
which, combined, realised the ideal of beauty were fully hers. I wondered as I looked at this

13:47.140 --> 13:53.820
fair creature, I admired her with my whole heart. Nature had surely formed her in a partial mood,

13:54.160 --> 14:00.160
and forgetting her usual stinted stepmother, Dole of Gifts, had endowed this, her darling,

14:00.160 --> 14:05.960
with a grand dame's bounty. What did St. John Rivers think of this earthly angel?

14:06.580 --> 14:11.560
I naturally asked myself that question as I saw him turn to her and look at her,

14:11.700 --> 14:17.540
and as naturally I sought the answer to the inquiry in his countenance. He had already

14:17.540 --> 14:22.820
withdrawn his eye from the parry, and was looking at a humble tuft of daisies which grew by the

14:22.820 --> 14:29.100
wicket. A lovely evening, but late for you to be out alone, he said, as he crushed the snowy heads

14:29.100 --> 14:35.860
of the closed flowers with his foot. Oh, I only come home from S. She mentioned the name of a large

14:35.860 --> 14:41.660
town, some twenty miles distant, this afternoon. Papa told me you had opened your school, and that

14:41.660 --> 14:47.460
the new mistress was come, and so I put on my bonnet after tea, and ran up the valley to see her.

14:47.700 --> 14:55.460
This is she, pointing to me. It is, said St. John. Do you think you shall like Morton?

14:55.460 --> 14:59.180
She asked of me, with a direct and naïve simplicity of tone and manner,

14:59.560 --> 15:04.660
pleasing, if childlike. I hope I shall. I have many inducements to do so.

15:05.260 --> 15:07.940
Did you find your scholars as attentive as you expected?

15:08.760 --> 15:11.320
Quite. Do you like your house?

15:12.120 --> 15:15.100
Very much. Have I furnished it nicely?

15:15.920 --> 15:21.020
Very nicely, indeed. And made a good choice of an attendant for you in Alice Wood?

15:21.680 --> 15:24.560
You have, indeed. She is teachable and handy.

15:25.520 --> 15:30.500
This, then, I thought, is Miss Oliver, the heiress, favoured, it seems, in the gifts of fortune,

15:30.820 --> 15:35.780
as well as in those of nature. What happy combination of the planets presided over her

15:35.780 --> 15:41.840
birth, I wonder? I shall come up and help you to teach sometimes, she added. It will be a change

15:41.840 --> 15:48.360
for me to visit you now and then. And I like a change. Mr. Rivers, I have been so gay during

15:48.360 --> 15:54.840
my visit to S. Last night, or rather this morning, I was dancing till two o'clock. The Nth Regiment

15:54.840 --> 16:00.240
are stationed there since the riots. And the officers are the most agreeable men in the world.

16:00.580 --> 16:04.080
They put all our young knife-grinders and scissor-merchants to shame.

16:04.620 --> 16:10.580
It seemed to me that Mr. St. John's underlip protruded, and his upper lip curled a moment.

16:11.060 --> 16:17.200
His mouth certainly looked a good deal compressed, and the lower part of his face unusually stern and

16:17.200 --> 16:22.840
square, as the laughing girl gave him this information. He lifted his gaze, too, from the

16:22.840 --> 16:29.880
daisies and turned it on her. An unsmiling, a searching, a meaning gaze it was. She answered it

16:29.880 --> 16:35.700
with a second laugh, and laughter well became her youth, her roses, her dimples, her bright eyes.

16:36.100 --> 16:39.800
As he stood mute and grave, she again felt caressing Carlo.

16:40.500 --> 16:48.260
Poor Carlo loves me, said she. He is not stern and distant to his friends, and if he could speak,

16:48.540 --> 16:55.120
he would not be silent. As she patted the dog's head, bending with native grace before his young

16:55.120 --> 17:02.060
and austere master, I saw a glow rise to that master's face. I saw his solemn eye melt with

17:02.060 --> 17:09.140
sudden fire, and flicker with resistless emotion. Flushed and kindled thus, he looked nearly as

17:09.140 --> 17:16.820
beautiful for a man as she for a woman. His chest heaved once, as if his large heart, weary of

17:16.820 --> 17:23.600
despotic constriction, had expanded, despite the will, and made a vigorous bound for the attainment

17:23.600 --> 17:31.120
of liberty. But he curbed it, I think, as a resolute rider would curb a rearing steed. He

17:31.120 --> 17:35.520
responded neither by word nor movement to the gentle advances made him.

17:36.440 --> 17:41.280
"'Papa says you never come to see us now,' continued Miss Oliver, looking up.

17:41.460 --> 17:46.960
"'You are quite a stranger at Vale Hall. He is alone this evening, and not very well.

17:47.320 --> 17:49.140
Will you return with me and visit him?'

17:49.940 --> 17:55.300
"'It is not a seasonable hour to intrude on Mr. Oliver,' answered St. John.

17:55.740 --> 18:02.380
"'Not a seasonable hour, but I declare it is. It is just the hour when Papa most wants company,

18:02.380 --> 18:09.940
when the works are closed, and he has no business to occupy him. Now, Mr. Rivers, do come. Why are

18:09.940 --> 18:16.580
you so very shy, and so very somber?' She filled up the hiatus, his silence left by a reply of her

18:16.580 --> 18:23.280
own. "'I forgot,' she exclaimed, shaking her beautiful curled head, as if shocked at herself.

18:23.660 --> 18:30.080
"'I am so giddy and thoughtless. Do excuse me. It had slipped my memory that you have good reasons

18:30.080 --> 18:37.500
to be indisposed for joining in my chatter. Diana and Mary have left you, and Morehouse is shut up,

18:37.600 --> 18:43.040
and you are so lonely. I am sure I pity you. Do come and see Papa.'

18:44.500 --> 18:47.580
"'Not to-night, Miss Rosamond, not to-night.'

18:48.580 --> 18:55.420
Mr. St. John spoke almost like an automaton. Himself only knew the effort it cost him thus to

18:55.420 --> 19:02.220
refuse. "'Well, if you are so obstinate, I will leave you, for I dare not stay any longer. The

19:02.220 --> 19:08.760
dew begins to fall. Good evening.' She held out her hand. He just touched it.

19:09.180 --> 19:15.960
"'Good evening,' he repeated in a voice low and hollow as an echo. She turned, but in a moment

19:15.960 --> 19:23.440
returned. "'Are you well?' she asked. Well might she put the question. His face was blanched as her

19:23.440 --> 19:30.900
head fell down. "'Quite well,' he enunciated, and with a bow he left the gate. She went one way, he

19:30.900 --> 19:37.680
another. She turned twice to gaze after him, as she tripped fairy-like down the field. He, as he

19:37.680 --> 19:43.860
strode firmly across, never turned at all. This spectacle of another's suffering and sacrifice

19:43.860 --> 19:50.000
wrapped my thoughts from exclusive meditation on my own. Diana Rivers had designated her brother

19:50.000 --> 19:53.680
inexorable as death. She had not exaggerated."

